# Testing Conventions

## Philosophy

Test behaviour, not implementation. Write tests that give you confidence to ship, not tests that break when you refactor. Prefer real objects over mocks. Hit the database. Render the views. Click the buttons.

User-facing copy and **`I18n.t`** in assertions: **`rules/i18n.mdc`**, **`skills/writing-i18n/references/patterns.md`** § Testing.

> **Tooling note:** DHH and 37signals use Minitest with fixtures. The testing
> *philosophy* here — system tests as backbone, real objects, behaviour over
> implementation — is theirs. The tooling (RSpec, FactoryBot, Capybara DSL)
> is an adaptation of that philosophy for teams that prefer RSpec.

## Test Pyramid (DHH Style)

The 37signals testing philosophy inverts the traditional pyramid — system tests are the backbone, not the afterthought:

1. **System specs** — the primary testing tool. Simulate real user flows through the browser. Most features should have system specs.
2. **Request specs** — test HTTP layer for redirects, auth, and response codes. Use for anything system specs can't cover.
3. **Model specs** — test domain logic, scopes, state transitions, and validations. The unit test of Rails.
4. **Everything else** — job specs, mailer specs, concern specs. Write them when the object has meaningful logic worth testing in isolation.

## RSpec Conventions

```ruby
# Describe the class or feature, not the test
RSpec.describe Article, type: :model do
  # One context per scenario
  context "when published" do
    # Test names read as sentences
    it "is visible to readers" do
      article = create(:article, :published)
      expect(article).to be_published
    end
  end
end
```

- `describe` for the class or method under test
- `context` for a specific scenario (always starts with "when" or "with")
- `it` for the assertion (reads as a sentence)
- One assertion per test when practical — multiple assertions are fine when testing one behaviour
- Avoid deep `let` / `subject` chains that obscure what's being tested — inline setup is clearer. A single `let` for the authenticated user is pragmatic; five nested `let`s are not.

## FactoryBot

Use `create` by default — hit the database. Use `build` only when persistence is irrelevant to the test. Use `build_stubbed` rarely — the speed gain is marginal and the behaviour drift from real records can mask bugs.

```ruby
# Define minimal factories — only required fields
FactoryBot.define do
  factory :article do
    title { "Sample Article" }
    association :author, factory: :user

    trait :published do
      after(:create) { |article| article.publish }
    end
  end
end
```

- Traits for states: `:published`, `:archived`, `:with_comments`
- Sequences for uniqueness: `sequence(:email) { |n| "user#{n}@example.com" }`
- No inheritance hierarchies — keep factories flat with traits
- Override in the test when the value matters to the assertion

## Each Behaviour Has One Home

Every behaviour is tested in exactly one place. Duplication across spec types
is waste — it slows the suite, obscures what each layer actually proves, and
creates maintenance drag when behaviour changes.

### Ownership by Layer

| Behaviour | Tested in | NOT tested in |
|-----------|-----------|---------------|
| Domain logic (publish, close, scopes) | Model spec | System/request spec don't re-test the logic |
| User flow (fill form, click, see result) | System spec | Request spec doesn't duplicate the flow |
| HTTP concerns (status codes, redirects) | Request spec | System spec doesn't assert status codes |
| Policy logic (who can do what) | Policy spec | Request spec doesn't re-test policy logic; it tests the HTTP gate |
| Auth gates at the HTTP layer | Request spec — **always**, even if a system spec exists | Auth is critical enough to test at the HTTP layer |
| Job performs work correctly | Job spec | Model spec just asserts `have_enqueued_job` |
| Mailer content | Mailer spec | Request spec just asserts delivery was enqueued |

Mailer classes, previews, `deliver_later`, and template layout: **`rules/mailers.mdc`**, **`skills/writing-mailers/references/patterns.md`**.

### The Rule

If a system spec already proves the user can create an article (fills form,
clicks save, sees the article), **don't** write a request spec that posts
the same params and checks the same record was created. The request spec
should only exist if it tests something the system spec can't: a specific
status code, a redirect chain, or rate limiting.

If a model spec proves `article.publish` creates a publication record,
the system spec just clicks "Publish" and asserts the page shows "Published"
— it doesn't also check `article.publication.present?`.

### Within a Single Spec File

Don't test the same path twice with different wording:

```ruby
# Bad — two tests for one behaviour
it "publishes the article" do
  article.publish
  expect(article).to be_published
end

it "creates a publication record" do
  article.publish
  expect(article.publication).to be_present
end

# Good — one test, multiple assertions for one behaviour
it "publishes the article" do
  article.publish

  expect(article).to be_published
  expect(article.publication).to be_present
  expect(article.publication.publisher).to eq(Current.user)
end
```

Multiple assertions in one test are fine when they verify the same action.
Split tests when the *setup* differs (different context), not when you want
to assert more things about the same outcome.

## What NOT to Do

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| Mocking ActiveRecord | Use real records via FactoryBot |
| Testing private methods | Test through public interface |
| `allow_any_instance_of` | Inject the dependency or test through the real path |
| Shared examples for unrelated specs | Inline the assertion — duplication is fine |
| `before(:all)` for database records | `before(:each)` or inline `create` |
| Testing framework behaviour (validates presence) | Test your domain logic, not Rails |
| Deep `let` / `subject` chains that obscure setup | Inline setup — each test tells its own story; a single `let` for auth user is fine |
| Controller specs | Request specs (controller specs are deprecated) |
| `stub_const` / `allow(ENV)` | Use Rails credentials or test configuration |
| Request spec duplicating a system spec flow | Request spec only for HTTP-layer concerns |
| System spec asserting model internals | System spec asserts what the user sees |
| Re-testing domain logic in integration specs | Model spec owns the logic; integration asserts the outcome |
| Separate tests for each assertion on one action | Multiple assertions in one test for one behaviour |
| Testing the same happy path in model + request + system | One home per behaviour — pick the right layer |
| Standalone `not_to` assertions that only prove absence | Assert the positive behaviour the user *does* see; `not_to` is a side-effect assertion, not a primary one |

### Do not write specs to prove code was removed

A spec whose only assertion is `not_to have_*` does not test behaviour — it tests absence. Such tests pass trivially (including when the feature never existed), document nothing about what users *can* do, and break silently if the element is renamed.

```ruby
# Bad — proves nothing except an element is absent; passes even if the page is empty
it "does not show an excluded agencies section" do
  expect(page).not_to have_link("New Excluded Agency")
end

# Good — tests what the user actually sees and can do on this page
it "shows the agencies list without the excluded agency option" do
  visit agencies_path
  expect(page).to have_content("Agencies")
  expect(page).to have_link("New Agency")
end
```

`not_to` is valid as a **secondary assertion** when it confirms a visible state change alongside a positive assertion:

```ruby
# Fine — not_to confirms the item is gone after deletion, paired with a positive outcome
it "user deletes an article" do
  article = create(:article, title: "To Delete")
  visit article_path(article)
  click_button "Delete"

  expect(page).to have_content("Article deleted.")  # primary
  expect(page).not_to have_content("To Delete")     # confirms removal
end
```

The rule: every test must have at least one positive assertion. A test that consists only of `not_to` is not a test — it is a removal receipt.

## Database Strategy

Use `database_cleaner` with transaction strategy for speed. System specs use truncation (Capybara runs in a separate thread).

```ruby
# rails_helper.rb
config.use_transactional_fixtures = true
```

For parallel test execution, ensure each process has its own database.
RSpec with `parallel_tests` gem or Rails' built-in `parallelize` both
handle this — but beware that shared state (sequences, unique constraints)
can cause flakiness across processes.

## Test File Naming

| Type | Location | Naming |
|------|----------|--------|
| Model | `spec/models/article_spec.rb` | Matches model name |
| Request | `spec/requests/articles_spec.rb` | Matches controller/resource |
| System | `spec/system/articles_spec.rb` | Matches feature or user flow |
| Factory | `spec/factories/articles.rb` | Plural model name |
| Job | `spec/jobs/notify_subscribers_job_spec.rb` | Matches job name |
| Mailer | `spec/mailers/notification_mailer_spec.rb` | Matches mailer name |
| Concern | `spec/models/concerns/publishable_spec.rb` | Matches concern name |
| Policy | `spec/policies/article_policy_spec.rb` | Matches policy name |
